16 0 19 Beech Forest~
.Stories go that at one time a young apprentice sorceress betrayed her
master and fled with one of his powerful spell books.  She traveled the
land, in constant fear of him coming to seek revenge.  After many years
of the roaming life, the apprentice at last made her way to an isolated
forest in the gentle northern mountains.  Nearby villagers used to go to
the young woman for advice, for although young, she had learned much from
the mystic book, and the simple rural people were impressed with her
parlor magics.  Several years passed of this humble life and the
sorceress became increasingly bold in her claims of power, often
remarking on her notable heritage.

That winter strange sights were seen around the village, large rats began
to infest the grain stores and food and clothing started to go missing. 
The villagers began to think they were haunted and sent some of their
warriors to seek help.  It would be these few that would live.  As winter
came to an end, sightings of rats became more and more frequent.  Some
swore that these rats wore clothes and stood upright, but glimpses were
fleeting and easily dismissed as imagined.  Then on the first day of
spring, a terrible storm blew up and crowded around the village.  A voice
boomed from out of the darkened clouds, "Fools, you have sheltered my
apprentice and now you shall feel my displeasure".  The master extracted
a terrible revenge; fire and lightning rained from the sky, reducing the
village to ruins and killing all of the villagers.  Then, as if in shame,
he commanded the forest to bury the destruction in a blanket of thorns. 
Even these were tainted with vengeful magics, twisting into dark
blood-red thorn bushes.  Once buried, the master constructed guardians to
keep prying eyes from the area.  What fate befell his apprentice is
unknown, although undoubtedly it was as terrible a deed as that suffered
by the villagers.

Several years later, travelers to the forest reported strange sights; men
made of sticks walking in the woods, and of a stone statue that weeps
blood.  Visitors are often advised to avoid these woods, for fear of
incurring the wrath of the sorcerer's curse.~

