-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=> MARMOR <=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

Although mobs can wear any piece of armor via mreset, the code does not add up
the AC of the items worn in order to determine how well they take a hit.  Mobs
use a code function called marmor to calculate which 'body part' is struck,
and then how well that body part can absorb a blow.  Builders can set up to 5
unique 'body parts', and assign an AC value to that setting.

Every time a mob is struck by a player, the code rolls a number from 1-1000.
If the number falls in the range of a particular body part, its AC is used
in the calculation of damage, and its name is displayed in combat. (ie: your
slash MUTILATES a bugbear raider's <fur-covered leg>).

The amount of AC that should be set (regardless of whatever a mob is wearing)
can be figured using the standards displayed in the help file mob_standards.

CONTEXT:

MARMOR #   %  AC BODYPART
MARMOR 1  333 19 fur-covered leg
MARMOR 2  666 20 furry belly
MARMOR 3 1000 18 snarling face

#        = position # to edit (1-5)
%        = percentage of this body part being hit
AC       = the AC value of this body part (how much damage is reduced)
BODYPART = The name of the body part being struck

In this case, if the combat roll falls from 1-333, the leg will be hit, and
333-666 will strike the furry belly.  Striking the leg will deduct damage as
if the mob was wearing AC19 armor in that location, and the belly 20 AC, etc.

Marmor values should grow in percentage value down the list, and the last
setting must be set to 1000.

