-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=> MRESETS <=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

Mobs can wear or hold just about anything you want them to.  This command is
used to let mobs wear armor, wield weapons, hold items in inventory, etc.

To add an item to a mob's inventory, you must be holding an example of the
item first (oload to yourself), then 'mreset <item keyword>'  It will be added
to the mreset list.

To delete an item from a mob's mreset list, type 'mreset # delete'

To see the list of mresets on a particular mob, type mreset by itself.

Example:

Nmbr Rrl  1_Ch 2_Ch 3_Ch  Rust Posi Liq Flags Vnum Descr
---- ---  ---- ---- ----  ---- ---- --- ----- ---- -----
[ 1] *     20%   0%   0%       Body           2002 hard leather jerkin
[ 2]       80%   0%   0%       Body           2001 soft leather tunic
[ 3] *     20%   0%   0%       Arms           2042 hard leather sleeves
[ 4]       80%   0%   0%       Arms           2041 soft leather sleeves
[ 5] *     20%   0%   0%       Legs           2022 hard leather leggings
[ 6]       80%   0%   0%       Legs           2021 soft leather leggings
[ 7] *     10%   0%   0%       rHnd           3025 double-stranded whip
[ 8]       90%   0%   0%       rHnd           3023 leather whip

RRL (Re-roll)    : To toggle this function, type mreset # -1 (off) or +1 (on)
                   Whenever a * is present, from that point on the code will
                   roll a new percentage chance for an object to reset.
                   (Total # of *'s = max # of objects a mob might hold)
                   This is used if you want to have a chance for different
                   kinds of objects to reset in the same position.

1_ch             : 1st chance.  Percentage chance that an item will load.
                   For every * Rrl, a 1-100 die is rolled.
                   The code will go through the list of mresets until a new
                   * is listed, and determine if/which objects get reset.
                   Place the rarest objects first on the list.

2_ch             : For an even harder (or a better 'random' roll) chance at
                   resetting an item, you can 'link' rolls together.  If a
                   value is set in 2_ch next to a 1_ch value, it will roll
                   a 1-100 number for 1_ch.  If 1_ch 'passes' its reset %,
                   then a new 1-100 number will be rolled for 2_ch.  If that
                   roll passes its 2_ch %, then the object will load.
                   (ie: 1_ch 50, 2_ch 50 = 50% of 50%, which gives 25%)

3_ch             : Same as 2_ch, but extends it out to a third roll.

Rust             : If an object is made out of a tarnishable metal, this is
                   the % chance that it will load in some sort of tarnished or
                   rusty condition.  Whether an object is slightly or very
                   rusty cannot be pre-set, the code randomly selects the
                   level of rust.  Most objects should be set in the 95-99%
                   range unless its description/rarity dictates otherwise.

Posi             : The position where a mob will be wearing the item.  If you
                   are resetting armor, which body part is this item worn?
                   Weapons go in right.hand or left.hand.  Don't reset an item
                   in a slot it shouldn't be in.  Type <mreset # posi> to see
                   the list of potential slots.  Inv = Inventory.  Means the
                   mob is holding the item but not wearing it.

Liq              : If a mob is holding/wearing a drink container, this field
                   determines what kind of liquid it will be filled with.
                   <mreset # liq> shows a list of choices.  If your container
                   always seems to reset empty even if a liquid is chosen,
                   see the note about object value settings.

Flags            : Two position flags are possible for objects.  If an object
                   is designed to be a container (ie: You want a mob to hold
                   a bag full of rocks in his inventory), you need to flag it
                   as +C for container.  <mreset # +C>.  A container should be
                   the last thing you reset on a mob, except for what might go
                   inside of the bag (it's just easier to read that way).
                   To mreset an item inside of a container, mreset the inside
                   object(s) after the container item, and flag them +I for
                   inside. <mreset # +I>  Containers and inside items can have
                   their own % resets.  Inside items will not reset unless the
                   container makes its reset chance.

Vnum             : The object # of the item being mreset.

Descr            : A quick description of the object being mreset.

