16 0 25 Object_Opcodes~
.@YOBJECT OPCODES@n

@CWEAPONS - Hit opcode@n

@cRepetition@n
As a general rule, opcodes on weapons should fire at a 10% ratio
or less, with a sliding scale based on weight.  A special-equipped
weapon's base opcode (excluding lucky looped extra hits) should not
go off more than three times in one battle.  The heavier the weapon,
the less its opcode will even be able to appear because it won't swing
as often, and vice versa for the light unarmed weapons, so adjust
accordingly.  The reason for this rule is because of how a weapon will
perform and look in combat.

@cOpcode Damage@n
Weapons should not have an opcode that strikes for more damage than a
base hit from the weapon unless extreme circumstances warrant it.
As a general rule, opcode hits should do around 50% of the damage of a
base hit.  Extreme care and extensive playtesting should be done to make
sure that a weapon's overall average damage comes as close as possible to
the max damage rating of the weapon's final level so it balances out with
a base weapon of that level.  A level 30 weapon with opcodes should not
outperform a base L30 weapon of the same variety (it just looks prettier).

@cLevel Penalties@n
A wide range of considerations goes into the determination of what level an
object with opcodes will possess, to include repetition, additional damage,
weight, oflags, etc.  There is no set formula to determine exactly how a
weapon will turn out.  As a basic guide, figure out the weapon's level for
its base damage and then add extra levels based on how much extra damage
the opcode will provide as a long-term average.  An additional method would
be to determine what level you want the weapon to end up as and downsize the
base damage to 'make room' for the opcode.  Final level statistics will be
determined during object review and approval.

@cMiscellaneous Information@n
The main thing to think about with opcodes is to test how it will perform
in the hands of a real player in real combat.  People like shiny objects.
If it goes off to little it 'sucks' and people despise it.  Go off too often,
and people will complain that they don't have one.  Great care should be taken
to make sure a special weapon actually balances out with its bland counterpart
for numbers, but also its looks as well.~

