16 0 16 programs 1 - basics~
.@M *** INTRODUCTION *** @n

This is the first of three helpfiles designed to help builders with
programs within the mud.  This file deals more or less with basics of
programming in general feel free to skip this file and continue to the
others if you have any programming or math background.

@M *** BASIC CONCEPTS *** @n
A program is a set of instructions.  The computer executes these
instructions from top to bottom.  When it reaches the end the program is
finished.

@C Vocabulary @n

@G";"@n This symbol is used to indicate the end of one instruction.  (in
general you should only have one instruction per line) 

@G"( and )"@n Brackets.  These are used to enclose a list of parameters
or arguments.  Each parameter or argument is seperated by a comma (",").
Also used as in math to dictate precendance of equations.

@GParameter@n defines what data a function requires.

@GArgument@n data passed to a function. Must match the functions parameters.

@GFunction@n You can think of this as a sub-program.  When a function is
called it does its stuff then the program from which it was called
continues.
A function is recognisable by the brackets after its name. This is for the parameter list.

@G"{ or }"@n Braces. Used to enclose a block of instructions.

@GBlock@n A group of instructions.

@GInteger@n Whole numbers (e.g. -59, 0, 1, 30000000 )

@GString@n A bunch of letters or numbers, enclosed in qoutes. (e.g. "hello", "eighty8 is great" )

@GCompile@n In our case this means check that the program works.  (this
is not 100% true here.  and compile has a different meaning in reality) 

@GNull@n This means literally "nothing".

@GBoolean@n This basically means true or false.

@GVariable@n Variables are like little cupboards that store a value. 
They can be of different types, integer, string or pointer variables for
example.

@GPointer@n This is like a little sign that points to some entity.  Such
as a character or a room in our case.

@C MUD PROGRAMS @n

In terms of the mud we have three times of programs:
Room programs (often refered to as acodes)
Mobile programs (often refered to as mpcodes)
Object programs (often refered to as opcodes )

These all operate more or less in exactly the same manner.

@M *** CONSTRUCTS *** @n

@C If statements @n
An if statement consists of a boolean condition and some instruction.
If the condition is true the instructions are carried out.  if false they
are skipped, the program continues from immediately after the if.

if statements are where blocks come into play, the instruction for an if
may be a block of instructions.

@YExample@n
if( i > 0 )
  eat_pie();

@YOr with a block@n
if( i > 0 ) {
  drink_coke();
  eat_pie();
}

@RNote@n there is no ";" after the if.

An if statement may be followed by and else.  An else is simply an
instruction (or block) that will be carried out in the case that the if
immediately preceeding it is false.

@YExample@n
if( i > 0 ) {
  eat_pie();
  drink_coke();
}
else {
  eat_cookie();
  drink_milk();
}
So if "i" is greater than 0.  we eat pie, drink coke and are done.  if
"i" is not greater than 0 we eat cookie, drink milk and are done.

@RNote@n An else refers to the _last_ if statement.  Only one else may be
used per if (don't laugh this is no so obvious to many people at first)

@C Loops @n

A loop is an instruction (or block) that is executed repeatedly a number
of times.  Don't worry about how many times for now.

They are defined like this:
loop( ) {
  eat_cookie();
  drink_milk();
}

This means we will continually drink milk and eat cookie until the loop is finished.

@BSee also "help programs 2" and "help programs 3"
~

.~

