16 0 19 Talidar's Spire~
.Tales told in the Red Fox Inn tell of the founding of the humble village
of Talidar's spire.  The story itself is a winter's favorite, its length
growing with each passing year, as are the deeds and trials that Talidar,
the town's founder had to face.  Although most of the tale is lost in
myth, some still rings true.

Talidar was a monk of Slen who was often wandering, as he would say,
before disappearing into a dark hole or similarly dangerous place, "off
to test the will of Slen and see how lucky I am today".  After many years
of Slen's blessings, the monk (often called the 'mad' monk) arrived in
the northern lands of heavy forests and rolling hills.  It's said he fell
in love with the land and its wilderness, marveling at the beauty he saw.

At that time long past, most humans lived in the warmer southern lands,
only a few brave souls had made the journey to the northern frontier.

One day while wandering, Talidar saw a beam of sunlight break through the
pendulous clouds that had hung overhead for days and shine upon a spire
of stone, rising above the black beech forest.  He hastened to the spot
(here the story seems to be in disagreement, some people tell of
Talidar's companion, an elven woman whose name is lost to time, spotting
the spire while Talidar was asleep, waiting for his dinner to cook).  It
is not wise to mention this version to the good patrons of the Red Fox -
not unless you have a few coppers spare to calm a loud and agitated crowd.

Nevertheless, on investigation of the spire, Talidar discovered the
symbol of Slen (the spinning coin) carved into the rock.  The writing was
ancient and weatherworn, dating to a time when legends walked the lands. 
Talidar was convinced that he had found a holy site and at once began to
construct a temple to honor Slen at the spire's apex.

After several failed attempts (Talidar was not a carpenter), the temple
lay in bits at the base of the spire.  Trusting in luck, Talidar decided
he would journey to the southern lands and hire an army of faithful
followers to aid in the construction of his grand temple.

Talidar spent over a year wandering the northern lands (by all accounts
he was completely lost) until he stumbled upon a small dwarven hunting
party.  Talidar immediately set about convincing these new allies (as he
saw them) that they should journey with him back to the holy site of Slen. 
Now normally the dwarven peoples are not followers of Slen, preferring a
more solid and dependable god, but as luck would have it a young scout,
named Khahindar, was moved by the monk's words and decided to accompany
Talidar on his quest.

And so Talidar's wanderings continued for many years (some say five,
others over a decade).  As he journeyed, so did his band of followers
grow and Talidar lead them all back to the spire.  (The exact number of
followers seems to grow with each recounting; the latest number being
above three hundred, but this seems unlikely).

At last they reached "the promised land" around Slen's spire (as it was
called in those days).  The temple to the goddess of luck was raised at
the top of the spire, and indeed, it seemed as if Slen's blessings were
upon the land.  The surrounding forests were laden with animals and fruit
that provided wood, food and skins.  The rich soil underfoot was perfect
for the growing growing crops, and the ample warm days of summer and
rainy winters to fed the land.

Nestled around the spire, the village grew and flourished for many years,
until at the end of one particularly harsh winter, news was brought to
the village from the temple.  Talidar had died in his sleep at aged one
hundred and twenty seven.  (Do not bother to dispute his age, it just
makes the locals demand even more ale from your now dwindling purse).

In honor of their founder the villagers renamed the spire Talidar's Spire
and eventually the village and its surroundings absorb the name as well.

Present day:
The village is well situated, nestled in the forest hills of the northern
lands.  Crops, such as apples and pumpkins, are shipped with wood to
places such as Ceanshire, and even as far as the southern cities. 
Especially valuable are the white teak trees that are found throughout
the area, sought after by furniture makers and other craftspeople for its
ease of shaping and its fine grain finish.

Apart from the occasional wolf or bear, the village is relatively
peaceful.  Several retired adventures have made their homes here, adding
their talents to the village.~

