131072 0 5 TFH.Object.Guide~
.@YGENERAL GUIDELINES WHEN MAKING OBJECTS@n

When creating a new object that is an improvement over a base item (or
creating a whole new class of object), use the following charts in order
to determine the item's level.

@YAFFECTS  (oset affect x)@n

@cbase stat@n (str, int, wis, dex, con):  +/- 20 levels per stat point.
@cresistance@n (cold, fire, poison, electricity, acid): +/- 1 level per 1%
@cstatistic boost@n (hit point, mana point, move point): +/- 1 level per 2 change
@cregen boost@n (hit regen, mana regen, move regen): +/- 2 levels per .1 change
@cccombat boost@n (hit/damroll) +5 for 1 level, +15 for 2 levels, +25 for 3@n
Do not use age, armor, or mind...  As of now they do nothing, and no
benefits to level will be given when using negative amounts of these.

@YOFLAGS (oflag x)@n

For the most part, oflags will be evaluated on a one-by-one basis.  As
far as I can tell, Jacob's help file @coflag_levels@n should still apply,
but I want to avoid having very many permanent-effect objects.

In general:

Making an item class or race-specific will reduce its level.  Try to
avoid too many of these, however, unless we can keep a good balance
between classes.  Making an item alignment-specific (good/neutral/evil)
will reduce its level.  As above, try to make sure the overall scheme of
things is balanced.

